    <item>
      <title>What is Linux? History, Philosophy &amp; Why It Dominates the World</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/linux/linux-fundamentals/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 12 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/linux/linux-fundamentals/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;What is Linux?&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;what-is-linux&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#what-is-linux&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Linux is a &lt;strong&gt;free, open-source, Unix-like operating system kernel&lt;/strong&gt; created by Linus Torvalds in 1991. At its core, the Linux kernel manages the hardware resources of a computer — CPU scheduling, memory allocation, device drivers, and I/O — and provides a foundation for software running above it.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;When most people say &amp;ldquo;Linux&amp;rdquo;, they mean a complete &lt;strong&gt;Linux distribution (distro)&lt;/strong&gt;: the kernel bundled with the GNU userland tools, a package manager, a shell (bash/zsh), and various software. Popular distros include:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Linux Commands Every DevOps Engineer Must Know</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/linux/linux-commands/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 02 Jan 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/linux/linux-commands/</guid>
      <description>&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Every command below is explained in plain English. If you are new to Linux, read the &amp;ldquo;What this does&amp;rdquo; section under each command — don&amp;rsquo;t just memorize the syntax, understand &lt;strong&gt;why&lt;/strong&gt; you are running it.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;How to Read Command Syntax&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;how-to-read-command-syntax&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#how-to-read-command-syntax&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Before we start, here is how to read the examples in this guide:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight-wrapper&#34;&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; class=&#34;chroma&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-text&#34; data-lang=&#34;text&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;command  -flag  argument&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;   |       |       |&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;   |       |    What you operate on (a file, a name, a path)&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;   |    Modifies how the command behaves&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;line&#34;&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;cl&#34;&gt;The program you are running&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;A &lt;code&gt;-&lt;/code&gt; followed by a single letter is a &lt;strong&gt;short flag&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;code&gt;-l&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;-a&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;-h&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;code&gt;--&lt;/code&gt; followed by a word is a &lt;strong&gt;long flag&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;code&gt;--all&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;--follow&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;--namespace&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;You can combine short flags: &lt;code&gt;-lah&lt;/code&gt; is the same as &lt;code&gt;-l -a -h&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Words in &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;angle brackets&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; are placeholders — replace them with your actual value&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;1. File &amp;amp; Directory Management&#xA;    &lt;div id=&#34;1-file--directory-management&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;    &lt;span&#xA;        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100 select-none&#34;&gt;&#xA;        &lt;a class=&#34;text-primary-300 dark:text-neutral-700 !no-underline&#34; href=&#34;#1-file--directory-management&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;    &lt;/span&gt;&#xA;    &#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;These are the commands you will use every single day. Master these first.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
